[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 outside China continues to grow and now totals 150. This includes 12 countries (including 1 territory) from the Western Pacific region, 55 countries (including 4 territories) from the European region, 8 from the Southeast Asia region, 17 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 34 countries (including 8 territories) from the Americas region, and 24 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

The total number of cases reported from outside of China is now 86 434, including 3388 deaths. The countries of the WHO/EURO region have reported a total of 56 834 cases (64.9% of total cases reported outside of China) and in the past 24 hours have reported 10 668 newly confirmed cases representing 76.3% of the newly reported cases outside of China.

Figure 2 . Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases reported outside of China, by date of report and WHO region through [16 Mar 2020], at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the exponential growth in reported cases starting late February 2020, with the major driving force being the reported cases from Europe.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: it is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time I've accessed the Johns Hopkins website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have at times significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and, depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the Hopkins table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4). - Mod.MPP]
